Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome back to our 30th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Relative=
ly quiet week on our end, but a bunch of good stuff happening around the un=
iverse that we=E2=80=99re excited to share.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Wander [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/1c454929-546c-4543-9160-6b3e16e1181d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ=
3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Wander [ https://substack.com/redirect/1c454929-546c-4543-9160-6b3e16e1181d=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has g=
otten more clicks than any sponsor in the history of Not Boring=E2=80=A6and=
 there=E2=80=99s good reason: the vacation homes are exquisite. Puja and I =
are currently planning our next trip at a Wander=E2=80=A6maybe at Surfside =
Beach, looks lovely. Plus, its Atlas vacation rental REIT presents a unique=
 investment opportunity.=C2=A0
Wander [ https://substack.com/redirect/1c454929-546c-4543-9160-6b3e16e1181d=
?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] is a =
network of smart vacation homes that come with inspiring views, modern work=
stations, restful beds, hotel-grade cleaning and 24/7 concierge service =E2=
=80=93=E2=80=93 combining the quality of a luxury hotel with the space and =
comfort of a vacation home, only better. Wander is sweetening their offer f=
or Not Boring readers: you can use promo code notboring500 (case sensitive)=
 for $500 off your next trip. (Offer expires Friday 3/3 at 11:59pm ET). Exp=
lore now. [ https://substack.com/redirect/1c454929-546c-4543-9160-6b3e16e11=
81d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
But that=E2=80=99s only part of the story. Wander recently launched Atlas [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/efe9bc72-ae38-4f09-971a-d00e2ef890b2?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =E2=80=93=E2=
=80=93 a first-of-its-kind vacation rental REIT that gives you the chance t=
o own a piece of their magical portfolio of homes. With Atlas, accredited i=
nvestors have the opportunity to earn income and diversify their portfolio =
without the headache and hassle of buying a property, renting it out, or ma=
intaining it.
Plus, new Atlas investors may get the chance to invest in Wander=E2=80=99s =
next round of funding.=20
(1) Trial Run of 4-Day Workweek Wins Converts [ https://substack.com/redire=
ct/e52409c3-d82e-4761-84ff-a70541ac1cdf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Z=
lNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Lora Kelley [ https://substack.com/redirect/6821da41-dbea-42c5-aede-c5e78ff=
06bc4?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] =
for The New York Times
Fifty-six of the companies, or 92 percent, said they would continue with a =
four-day week, according to the new report, and 18 confirmed [ https://subs=
tack.com/redirect/2deb2c5f-22a6-4e47-bbcb-0f6b331a3a44?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qi=
fQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that the change would be p=
ermanent. The study also found that companies=E2=80=99 revenue stayed broad=
ly the same on average over the trial period =E2=80=94 and that attrition a=
mong employees dropped significantly. In a survey about halfway through the=
 study, most of the companies reported no loss of productivity [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/e8393ae3-b64e-4cd1-b8cf-7b270eb780ec?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3=
QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] during the trial.
Progress is great. There=E2=80=99s this pervasive fear that productivity ga=
ins will take everyone=E2=80=99s jobs, but as we wrote about in our piece o=
n Formic [ https://substack.com/redirect/b0125b46-7038-4503-97c7-571522c3c4=
43?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], wh=
at actually happens is that people find new, more interesting jobs. A much =
lower percentage of us work on farms to feed our families than we used to; =
now some people get to do silly things like write newsletters for work.=20
But something else happens, too. Instead of some people losing all of their=
 work, most people get to work less. Kids don=E2=80=99t go to work on the f=
amily farm at ten years old; they go to school. Fewer people work until the=
 day they die; many retire at 65. The two-day weekend, something we take fo=
r granted, didn=E2=80=99t become widespread until the 1930s.=20
Today, remote or hybrid work means less time commuting and more time at hom=
e. Some companies are even experimenting with a 4-Day Work Week, and the re=
sults of this study out of Britain are promising: less work, no productivit=
y loss.=20
We McCormick boys are no future of work experts. Our situation is unique: P=
acky and I both work from home, do some amount of =E2=80=9Cwork=E2=80=9D 7 =
days a week, maybe talk about work-related topics live once per quarter, se=
nd a few Slack messages a day, manage a small super-liquid team, and haven=
=E2=80=99t changed out of sweatpants in three years. Some people are workin=
g on all-consuming, ambitious missions that require seven days a week, in-p=
erson, and we=E2=80=99re all for that too. But if people in a lot of jobs c=
an get just as much shit done in four days as they do in five days, then wh=
y not give them back an extra day to pursue their non-work lives?=20
If all we get from this technological progress is 14% more time to do the t=
hings we love doing vs. working, that=E2=80=99s still pretty powerful.
Which is why we were pumped to see the positive results of the largest 4 Da=
y Work Week Trial ever:
92% of trial companies plan on continuing the 4 Day Work Week model
No reported loss of productivity
No measurable decrease in trial company revenue
Lower attrition rates
The real question is: we taking off Mondays or Fridays?
(2) Genetically Modified Trees Are Taking Root to Capture Carbon [ https://=
substack.com/redirect/5babc295-9b51-48b9-b8a7-9603ecb87ae1?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAw=
Z3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Margaret Osborne [ https://substack.com/redirect/c067ac28-5268-4dde-abc5-55=
14052fa8f3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for Smithsonian Magazine
The San Francisco-based venture, called Living Carbon, intends to plant 4 t=
o 5 million trees by the middle of next year, which they say will help with=
 the looming climate crisis [ https://substack.com/redirect/d98ae568-3aee-4=
fbc-861e-e728e6473edb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOs=
a8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. This may be the first time genetically modified trees have=
 been planted in a U.S. forest outside of a research trial or commercial fr=
uit orchard, per the New York Times [ https://substack.com/redirect/62277e3=
3-22da-4b84-81cf-90af9fb825ea?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]=E2=80=99 Gabriel Popkin.
There are two ways to reduce our carbon footprint:
Emit less carbon (most impactful)
Capture and remove carbon we=E2=80=99ve already emitted (less impactful, bu=
t still important)
We=E2=80=99ve written extensively about projects that are focusing on the l=
atter. Carbon removal is the focus of Frontier, the advance market commitme=
nt, lead by Stripe and other major tech companies, to buy an initial $925M =
of permanent carbon removal.
Living Carbon [ https://substack.com/redirect/1802d0da-a1bc-42fe-8c90-73ed7=
1a9908c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
], a SF-based startup that, as far as we can tell, is not associated with F=
rontier but is partnered with Stripe, recently became the first organizatio=
n to plant genetically modified trees in the U.S. outside of trial or comme=
rcial forests. The trees are designed to grow up to 53% larger, suck up 27%=
 more carbon, and store the carbon in a more permanent way than natural tre=
es. The startup plans on planting 4-5 million of these freak-trees in the n=
ext year and hope to capture 600 megatons by 2030. They won=E2=80=99t solve=
 climate change, but they=E2=80=99ll make a dent on removing carbon we=E2=
=80=99ve already emitted.
(3) Google=E2=80=99s quantum computer hits key milestone by reducing errors=
 [ https://substack.com/redirect/fc67577f-cc80-44a6-8723-2d1b064f1b92?j=3De=
yJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Davide Castelvecchi [ https://substack.com/redirect/cdfc1b64-3265-4824-82fc=
-37efbb35ccd8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] for Nature
Physicists at Google have reached what they describe as their second milest=
one along the path to a useful quantum computer. At a laboratory in Santa B=
arbara, California, they have demonstrated that they can lower the error ra=
te of calculations by making their quantum code bigger.
We will not attempt to explain this quantum computing milestone from a tech=
nical perspective =E2=80=94 that=E2=80=99s way above our paygrade. But the =
breakthrough, most easily summarized as error reduction in quantum computin=
g, is noteworthy because it=E2=80=99s the second of six milestones achieved=
 by Google on its roadmap to producing a =E2=80=9Cuseful quantum computer.=
=E2=80=9D
We don=E2=80=99t know exactly when quantum computing will be =E2=80=9Cusefu=
l=E2=80=9D but it=E2=80=99s worth noting that the progress does seem to be =
lining up with breakthroughs in AI. Quantum computers, in the simplest term=
s, allow for really big complex math problems to be performed more quickly.=
 That may be an understatement: quantum computers are 158 million times fas=
ter than the most sophisticated supercomputers in action today.=20
So imagine an AI that is run on a computer 158 million times more efficient=
 than whatever OpenAI is using today=E2=80=A6and then imagine what the worl=
d will look like with that type of AI running around. Eliezer weeps [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/e7b2fa54-65af-4ec7-b1aa-9210537b9b5e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
The big question is: when quantum computing is commercially viable, will Go=
ogle have what it takes to commercialize it, or will they really be the mod=
ern Xerox PARC?
(4) Technology over the long run: zoom out to see how dramatically the worl=
d can change within a lifetime [ https://substack.com/redirect/b16e14c6-f30=
8-4fa0-84fa-3af9fda58761?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Max Roser [ https://substack.com/redirect/3a3bf111-464f-4a87-a1ab-5440d0514=
d64?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] fo=
r Our World in Data
Speaking of imagining how technological progress will shape the future (and=
 the past), Our World in Data released a new report on technological progre=
ss throughout the course of history. The main takeaway for me is that the s=
lope of technological progress exploded upwards starting in the 1800s. We w=
ent a million years between controlled fire and the invention of the steam =
locomotive. And 145 years between the invention of the steam locomotive and=
 the first nuclear bomb.
Compounding is a hell of a drug, and save any catastrophic misstep, I antic=
ipate that society will continue to compound its way on the long upward slo=
pe of progress for the foreseeable future. The type of progress that humans=
 living today have experienced is more linear than exponential=E2=80=A6but =
the introduction of something like a quantum-powered AI might just shoot th=
at slope vertical. The not-so-distant future (100 years from now) will like=
ly be less recognizable to humans today than the distant past.=20
(5) Two Essays from Noah Smith [ https://substack.com/redirect/37bd4728-26f=
9-4dd5-bc31-2bc20d5fb671?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
Noah Smith [ https://substack.com/redirect/a6f2a32a-f1a5-43cf-b96a-451ffbd6=
1beb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] f=
or Noahpinion
We=E2=80=99ve said this before and we=E2=80=99ll say it again: if Noah Smit=
h keeps putting out bangers, we=E2=80=99re going to keep covering them. He =
published five worthwhile pieces in the last week alone, but we=E2=80=99ll =
focus on two:
The U.S. Cannot Afford to Turn Against Immigration [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/0842282f-d157-4aac-ad79-5af558be531f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]: In this piece, Smith makes the case=
 as to why the U.S. needs more immigration and offers a compromise to make =
immigration more palpable for anti-immigrationists.
Why we need immigration: =E2=80=9CWe need continued robust immigration flow=
s, especially of high-skilled immigrants, in order to keep our nation both =
prosperous and secure.=E2=80=9D Smith=E2=80=99s argument here is two-fold: =
immigration keeps the American populace young (undoubtedly a good thing) an=
d high-skilled immigration is crucial for invention and scientific research=
 (especially in the age of an AI-focused potential Second Cold War.)
Compromise: =E2=80=9CIncreased border security is paired with increased leg=
al pathways to immigration.=E2=80=9D Smith argues that the chaos brought on=
 by illegal immigration is not worth it. It=E2=80=99s a third rail issue th=
at muddies one issue (southwest border immigration) with another more impor=
tant issue (high-skilled labor immigration.) Tightening border policy quell=
s the anti-immigrationists fears and allows for a more productive conversat=
ion to be had about high-skilled immigration.=20
Don=E2=80=99t Be a Doomer [ https://substack.com/redirect/f2eadb09-d9b6-460=
8-b7ec-115b80dc9d54?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ]: This essay is Smith=E2=80=99s response to the below tweet fr=
om Taylor Lorenz. Listen, we=E2=80=99re not in the business of Lorenz-bashi=
ng (it=E2=80=99s a crowded and competitive industry) and neither is Smith. =
Smith=E2=80=99s rebuttal is a data-driven clear-headed response to the doom=
erism that Lorenz encapsulates in that tweet. Let=E2=80=99s go 1-by-1:
Critique of Late Stage Capitalism
Smith=E2=80=99s Response: =E2=80=9CEven as capitalism has conquered the wor=
ld, humanity is richer now than it has ever been, and for the last three de=
cades income growth has been concentrated in low-income countries [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/5bc9169c-9f76-4681-91f9-a3cebaafde85?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Poverty is down at e=
very level, not just in rates but in absolute numbers=E2=80=9D
U.S. has =E2=80=9C0 social safety net=E2=80=9D
Smith=E2=80=99s Response: =E2=80=9CU.S. public social spending has risen st=
eadily as a share of GDP. We have Social Security, SSDI, Medicare, Medicaid=
, unemployment insurance, Section 8 housing vouchers, SNAP, the EITC, the c=
hild tax credit, and many other safety net programs.=E2=80=9D
U.S. has =E2=80=9C0 job security=E2=80=9D
Smith=E2=80=99s Response: =E2=80=9CThe average tenure of employment [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/d29df223-9a9a-4142-97bb-117154d2e660?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] has stayed the same=
 since the 1990s [ https://substack.com/redirect/b2e531f6-51c2-46fc-8294-4a=
0cb005e991?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ]. Except for a spike during the pandemic, the layoff rate has fallen sl=
owly but steadily [ https://substack.com/redirect/f760c005-ac2e-4d78-9876-5=
4388ec9b24f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] since the turn of the century.=E2=80=9D
Covid
Smith=E2=80=99s Response: =E2=80=9CMeanwhile, despite a steady drumbeat of =
new variants, Covid deaths in the West are stable, with nothing like the bi=
g waves of the first two years. This is due in part to the amazing efforts =
of human science, which developed safe and effective vaccines in record tim=
e. Those vaccines are now reckoned to have saved millions of lives [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/af07d205-6fcb-4eb3-a067-4a3192039e0b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] in the U.S. alone, a=
nd tens of millions worldwide [ https://substack.com/redirect/f629e9ff-8cf3=
-4383-8e8a-4bdfa73cf4fa?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=E2=80=9D
Climate Change
Smith=E2=80=99s Response: =E2=80=9CClimate change is definitely going to be=
 a bumpy ride for the planet, and it=E2=80=99s not yet certain that we=E2=
=80=99ll defeat it in time to save ourselves from major harm. But recent pr=
ogress is extremely encouraging.=E2=80=9D
Once Smith properly addressed Lorenz=E2=80=99 claims, he delves into a full=
 explanation as to why this type of doomerism is net bad for the world: it =
doesn=E2=80=99t allow for focus on the most important problems (ie Long Cov=
id vs. Climate Change) and de-motivates people from trying to solve those p=
roblems.
We=E2=80=99re obviously in the optimistic camp here. We=E2=80=99re not blin=
d to the troubles of the world, but we subscribe to David Deutsch=E2=80=99s=
 Principle of Optimism states that =E2=80=9CAll evils are caused by insuffi=
cient knowledge.=E2=80=9D In order to cure those evils, we need to get back=
 to a society that prioritizes truth and doesn=E2=80=99t get caught up in d=
oomerism.
Did you enjoy reading this Weekly Dose of Optimism?
Yes [ https://substack.com/redirect/462707cc-1dc1-48cf-951a-cbe0ec2c1161?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] | Meh [=
 https://substack.com/redirect/462707cc-1dc1-48cf-951a-cbe0ec2c1161?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] | No [ https:=
//substack.com/redirect/462707cc-1dc1-48cf-951a-cbe0ec2c1161?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
(Powered by Sprig)
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox on Mo=
nday.
Thanks for reading,
Dan

